        keyRules:["E°cell = E°cathode - E°anode (both as reduction potentials). Positive E°cell → spontaneous galvanic cell.","ΔG° = -nFE°cell. If E°cell > 0 → ΔG° < 0 → spontaneous → K > 1.","Nernst: E decreases as products accumulate (Q increases). Cell runs until E = 0 (equilibrium reached).","Electrolysis: cathode is still reduction (metal deposits there). Anode is still oxidation (may dissolve or produce gas)."],
        resources:[{ name:"Chad's Prep — Electrochemistry", url:"https://www.chadsprep.com", desc:"Galvanic cells, Nernst equation, and electrolysis" }],
        frq:null,
        tip:"E°cell, ΔG°, and K are all connected: master this triangle. If you know any one, you can find the others. E°cell → ΔG° = -nFE° → K = e^(-ΔG°/RT). This relationship appears in FRQs every 2 years.",
