        keyRules:["Political socialization: family is the most powerful influence — most people adopt their parents' party identification. Party ID is the single best predictor of vote choice.","Electoral College: 270 of 538 needed. Winner-take-all means campaigns focus on swing states. Small states have more EC votes per capita than large states.","Interest groups vs political parties: parties seek to win elections and control government. Interest groups seek to influence policy without winning elections.","Agenda-setting: media doesn't tell us WHAT to think but WHAT to think about. By choosing what to cover, media shapes which issues are salient for voters."],
        resources:[{ name:"Heimler's History — Political Behavior", url:"https://www.youtube.com/@heimlershistory", desc:"Elections, parties, and participation review" }],
        frq:{ type:"FRQ — Quantitative Analysis", prompt:"Using a provided electoral map or voter turnout data: (a) describe the specific pattern shown in the data, (b) explain one factor that accounts for this pattern, (c) explain how this pattern affects the quality of democratic representation.", rubricTip:"AP Gov quantitative FRQ: always cite specific data from the provided source (name numbers or percentages). Then explain the mechanism behind the pattern. Then connect to a democratic principle (majority rule, political equality, or representative government). Each part earns 1-2 points." },
